<module status="bronze">
  <h>toponyms</h>
  <p>Toponyms are <a href="?xx=nouns/names">names</a> identifying places and other geographical
    entities.</p>
  <p>Like other kinds of name, toponyms can be classified into two grammatical types – <ul>
      <li><a href="?xx=nouns/toponymic_proper_nouns">toponymic proper nouns</a> – <g>Barraigh</g>
        <fem/>
        <en>Barra</en>, <g>Glaschu</g>
        <masc/>
        <en>Glasgow</en>, <g>Alba (Nuadh)</g>
        <fem/>
        <en>(Nova) Scotia</en>, <g>Sùilebheinn</g>
        <fem/>
        <en>Suilven</en>, <g>Foirthe</g>
        <fem/>
        <en>The Forth</en></li>
      <li><a href="?xx=nouns/toponymic_name_descriptions">toponymic name-descriptions</a> – <g>Am
          Ploc</g>
        <en>Plockton</en>, <g>Dùthaich MhicAoidh</g>
        <en>North Sutherland</en>, <g>Beinn a’ Bhreacaidh</g>
        <en>Ben Vrackie</en>, <g>An Linne Latharnach</g>
        <en>The Lorne Firth</en>.</li>
    </ul>
  </p>
